Q114:
CONSENT FOR PARTICIPATION IN A RESEARCH PROJECT
YALE UNIVERSITY SCHOOL OF MEDICINE – YALE-NEW HAVEN HOSPITAL 
Study Title: Neural correlates of decision-making processes – online Principal Investigator: Ifat Levy, PhD Funding Source: NIH and Departmental 
Invitation to Participate and Description of ProjectYou are invited to participate in a research study designed to examine how the brain works when we make decisions.
In order to decide whether you wish to be a part of this research study, you should know enough about its risks and benefits to make an informed judgment. This consent form gives you detailed information about the research study, which should go over all aspects of this research: its purpose, the procedures that will be performed, any risks of the procedures, and possible benefits. Once you understand the study, you will be asked if you wish to participate; if so, you will be asked to sign this form. 
Description of Procedures If you agree to participate, you will first complete an online task in which you will be asked to choose which of two options you prefer. For example, you might choose between a sure chance of winning a certain amount of money, and some probability of winning another amount.
At the end of the task, one of your choices will be randomly chosen and actualized for the chance of a real bonus payment.
Next, you will complete some questionnaires about your daily life, experiences, opinions, and beliefs.
You will also be asked to provide some basic information about yourself, such as your age and gender; you will have the option to decline to answer these questions. 
Risks and Inconveniences There are no known risks associated with subjects’ participation in this study beyond those associated with working at a computer terminal for a period of about 20 minutes. You will be able to take short breaks from time to time if needed. 
Benefits There will be no direct benefits to you of participating in this study. However, the results may be of benefit to others by contributing to our understanding of how decision-making processes are implemented by the brain. 
Economic Considerations There will be no cost to you associated with participation in this study. You will receive a minimum payment of $5 through Amazon Mechanical Turk for completing the study, with the chance to win an additional bonus payment during the task. 
Confidentiality The online survey will be anonymous; no identifiable information will be obtained. 
Voluntary Participation and Withdrawal Participation in this study is voluntary. You are free to choose not to take part in this study. Refusing to participate will involve no penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled (such as your health care outside the study, the payment for your health care, and your health care benefits). However, you will not be able to enroll in this research study and will not receive study procedures as a study participant if you do not allow use of your information as part of this study.
If you do become a participant, you may withdraw from this study at any time. If you chooseto withdraw during the task, you may do so by closing the browser window; your data will not be saved or used by the lab. 
QuestionsWe have used some technical terms in this form. Please feel free to ask about anything you don't understand and to consider this research and the consent form carefully – for as long as you feel is necessary – before you make a decision. 
Authorization I have read (or someone has read to me) this form and have decided to participate in the project described above. Its general purposes, the particulars of involvement, and possible hazards and inconveniences have been explained to my satisfaction

choice_strategy_conf: I considered the probabilities of the two choices along with the reward amount. I looked at the reward amount and how much upside it offered vs. the other option (like the guaranteed $5), and then also the range of probabilities on the riskier option. If the reward was high enough, I was generally very willing to risk the more volatile ranges (e.g. 10-90%), but more cautious on the smaller amounts. Even the ones at $12-$16 at 25-75% had me questioning whether it was worth going for what would be similar to a coin flip. So with the 10-90% options, I also instinctively thought of them as being somewhat like a 50-50, and whether I was willing to do a coin flip for that amount. If I hit the 90% side, then it's not guaranteed, but it's close enough.
choice_strategy_amb: Absolutely yes. I definitely made decisions differently when faced with the choices that included this type of option. With these, I considered the more variable range and how I felt about being able to land somewhere in the middle (e.g. 50% here). It also varied based on the specific range in the choice, like if it was a low probability (e.g. 0-30%). In those cases, I opted to do a coin flip for the highest percentage (e.g. going for the 0 or 30% disagreement choice instead of the 0-30% range of an agreed option).

For example, if one person says 10% chance and the other says 90%, it's very hard for me to just average those out to 50% chance, even though that's what I would normally do if I was thinking logically. Whereas if the disagreement was 40% versus 60%, I can very easily rationalize 50% in my mind as the average value. I'm more likely to take a gamble on a huge disparity (90% vs. 10%) if the reward is very large.
choice_strategy_amb: I tried not to let this difference influence me much, but admittedly it is much easier to pick an option if the people are agreeing on a range versus two stated extremes. It's more easy to think of an average in a range of values when people agree on the range, versus thinking of the average middle value with two people disagreeing strongly.
